TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Flash Crash: A Cautionary Tale About Highly Fragmented Markets
AU  - Menkveld, Albert J.
AU  - Yueshen, Bart Zhou
Y1  - 2018/11/05
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3040
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3040
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 4470
EP  - 4488
VL  - 65
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A breakdown of cross-market arbitrage activity could make markets more fragile and result in price crashes. We provide suggestive evidence for this novel channel based on a high-frequency analysis of the most salient crash in recent history: The Flash Crash. We further show that such an event can be extremely costly for a large seller trading in a particular venue as the seller effectively relies on local liquidity supply only. These findings highlight the vulnerability of today?s highly fragmented markets.This paper was accepted by Gustavo Manso, finance.
AB  - A breakdown of cross-market arbitrage activity could make markets more fragile and result in price crashes. We provide suggestive evidence for this novel channel based on a high-frequency analysis of the most salient crash in recent history: The Flash Crash. We further show that such an event can be extremely costly for a large seller trading in a particular venue as the seller effectively relies on local liquidity supply only. These findings highlight the vulnerability of today?s highly fragmented markets.This paper was accepted by Gustavo Manso, finance.
